# Initial problem text to explain the scaffolding setup.
BEGIN_PGML

Follow the steps to find the derivative of the given function in two different ways.

>>[``h(x) = ([$f])([$g])``]<<

This problem has three parts. You may only open the next part after correctly
completing the previous part.
END_PGML
#-ENDULETH-#

Scaffold::Begin();
#-ULETH-#
# For each part the answer or answer checker reference must appear in the curly 
# braces immediately after the answer field.
Section::Begin("Product Rule - Part 1");
# Part 1 problem text.
BEGIN_PGML
Let [`f(x) = [$f]`] and [`g(x) = [$g]`] so that [`h(x) = f(x) \cdot g(x)`]. 
Their respective derivatives are  

[`f'(x) = `][_____________]{Compute($df)} [@ AnswerFormatHelp("formulas") @]*  
and  
[`g'(x) = `][_____________]{Compute($dg)}.
END_PGML
Section::End();

Section::Begin("Product Rule - Part 2");
# Part 2 problem text.
BEGIN_PGML
Using the derivatives from Part 1 and the Product Rule,

[``h'(x) = \left[\frac{f}{g}\right]' 
= f'\cdot g + f\cdot g' = ``]
[`\Big(`][_____]{Compute($df)}[`\Big)`][`\cdot`][`\Big(`][_____]{Compute($g)}[`\Big)`] [`+`] [`\Big(`][_____]{Compute($f)}[`\Big)`][`\cdot`][`\Big(`][_____]{Compute($dg)}[`\Big)`].

Simplifying, we find that
[`h'(x) = `][_____]{$dh}.

END_PGML
Section::End();

Section::Begin("Algebraic Manipulation");
# Part 3 problem text.
BEGIN_PGML

You may use algebra to simplify [`h(x)`] before taking the derivative. In this instance, [`h(x)`] simplifies to [__________]{Compute($hsimple)}.

We may then use the Power Rule to determine that
[`h'(x) = `][_____]{Compute($dh)}.

END_PGML
Section::End();
#-ENDULETH-#

Scaffold::End();



###################################
#  Answer Evaluation 

#evaluation must be completed in the problem text

###################################
#  Solution

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION

First, using the Product Rule,

[``
  \begin{array}{rcl}
    h'(x) &=& \frac{d}{dx}[[$f]]\cdot([$g]) + ([$f])\cdot \frac{d}{dx}[[$g]] \\
    &&\\
    &=& ([$df])([$g]) + ([$f])([$dg]) \\
  \end{array}
``]

After simplifying the last line, we find [`h'(x) = [$dh]`].

Next, simplify [`h(x)`] first:

[``
  h(x) = ([$a])([$c])x^{[$b] + [$d]} = [$hsimple]
``]

Then, by Power Rule, we find [`h'(x) = [$dh]`].


END_PGML_SOLUTION

